    bug-system at MIT-OZ
Reply-to: JTW@MIT-MC
In-Reply-To: Your message of 7-Sep-83 2033-EDT

Well I think this is how it works...

In DEC's model, "archiving" something means to make a permanant record
of it on a tape somewhere. This tape file is then considered the canonical
one, and if you bring the file back to disk then the disk version is
just a more usable representation of the one on tape. Thus, the disk
version of an archived file is constrained to be unchangable as long
as the tape version continues to exist. If you want to modify an
archived-then-restored file, you have to copy it to a new file or
generation number. If you want to unarchive something completely,
use the "archive" subcommand to delete.
-------


