Cc: BUG-MAIL at MIT-MC, BUG-BABYL at MIT-MC
In-reply-to: The message of 16 Sep 83 17:34-EDT from Glenn S. Burke <GSB>

This is for GSB/Ellis's finger pointing session.

    Date:    Fri, 9 Sep 83 18:58:26 EDT
    From:    John R Ellis <Ellis@YALE.ARPA>

    We get so much garbage mail in over the net that has invalid, unrepliable
    From:  fields (from UUCP sites, BITNET sites, and especially recalcitrant
    ARPA sites) that we've changed our local mailer to change the From:  field
    to contain the "envelope from" if it is different from the From:, renaming
    the original From:  to be Unauthentic-From:.  For example:

In other words, YALE takes it upon themselves to munge up message
headers. Sigh, this must be the most popular way to lose in Internet
mail these days.  I think that since in the DoD Internet model the
header is part of the MESSAGE, and NOT part of the ENVELOPE, they
should not be breaking the message seal and scribbling all over the
contents.

There has been alot of discussion over this in relation to the NBS
model, which I understand makes clearer distinctions between envelope
and contents. (I haven't read it yet.) In the Internet though, there
is either no envelope, or maybe the transport mechanism (SMTP)
dynamically creates and uses the envelope as the Return-path.

    As far as incompetent mailers go, I notice that Info-Vax messages still
    come out with the old non-standard Remailed- headers instead of the 
    standard Resent-.

Ellis is correct here, RFC 822 (section 4.1, page 17, Message
Specification) says the field called "Resent-From".

    Also, Burke's to Meehan contained an address with invalid syntax; the
    new standard does not allow "."  in personal names unless it is enclosed
    in quotes.  

    Instead of:     From: Glenn S. Burke   <GSB @ MIT-MC>
    It should read: From: "Glenn S. Burke" <GSB @ MIT-MC>
    or:             From: Glenn S Burke    <GSB @ MIT-MC>


I am not sure if Ellis is right or not.
I think RFC 822 (section 6.2.4, page 30, Domain Dependant Local
String) says that                  <Glenn S. Burke @ MIT-MC>
is illegal, and that it should be  <"Glenn S. Burke" @ MIT-MC> .

But we are not talking about the mailbox name -- we are talking about
a comment included in part of the field.  Since we can unambiguously
parse out the legal net address by the brokets, I am not so sure if
comment quoting is required. I believe KLH does not think the quoting
is required in that part of the field, and that RFC822 is buggy if it
says otherwise.

Chris

