Date: 30 November 1983 04:37 EST
From: Kent M Pitman <KMP @ MIT-MC>
Subject: The J bug
To: ECC @ MIT-MC
cc: BUG-BABYL @ MIT-MC

I fixed & Jump to Current Survey Line to do something that seemed more
reasonable. The source is MC:EMACS1;BABYL 764 and I compiled it to 
ECC;XBABYL for maintainers to try out.

The old behavior was as follows:
 If it couldn't find the line for the message number it wanted,
 it would just blindly go back a line or forward a line (depending on
 if the number it wanted was bigger or smaller). This meant that 1J in
 a survey of messages 100-200 while at message 150 would take you to 
 message 149, which I think was confusing.

The new behavior is as follows:
 If it can't fine the exact line for the message number, it will
 try to find a line which is NUMBERED as close to that as possible
 (not necessarily textually near). It will prefer a smaller line number
 if moving backward or a larger line number if working forward. Hence,
 in the above example, 1J will go to line 100 (regardless of the order
 of the lines, in fact). Also, in a survey of only the odd line numbers
 from 101-199, from line 151, 
   doing 1J   will go to line 101,
   doing 106J will go to line 105,
   doing 196J will go to line 197

This algorithm takes slightly longer to run, but I think not significantly
longer. In contiguous and/or dense surveys (eg, from the B command)
where the exact target line number is likely to be found, it will be the
same speed as before. Only in sparse surveys is this new code likely to 
get used at all, but in those surveys I suspect correctness is worse any 
slight loss of speed anyway.

One important philosophical consequence of this change is that if you have
some survey like this where you have re-ordered the lines:

 No. Lines        From->To        Subject or Text
 14:   22  Blythe@OZ->            {RemindNow} Phone Msg: Call Dr. Liza Sisk
 22:   65  AGRE->                 {Seminar} Wed 30-Nov 4:00 "Problem Solver" !
 17:   88  BAGLEY%MIT-OZ.ARPA->co {Seminar} Cognitive Science Calendar

and you are at msg 14 and type D, it will jump to message 17. Formerly, it
used to go down a line to message 22. If this is an important intended
feature rather than just an accidental consequence of the way the code was
set up, then this "fix" is not correct and should be retracted.

Personally, I find Surveys to be sufficiently ephemeral (you have only
to breathe on the *Survey* buffer to have its contents erased) that I don't
do much line re-arrangement and in most cases where I did do such, I doubt
I would mind the new behavior a whole lot. But that's just my personal 
feeling and I wouldn't want to be accused of pushing my tastes upon others
without asking.

Gene, could you tell me if the high-level description of the changes I
made sound reasonable and -- if you get time -- check over the code itself
and make sure it looks ok? Thanks. --kmp

