The documentation for survey commands specifically leaves certain
argument cases undefined for some commands, because I didn't
think the behavior was clear or reasonable -- it was just what
fell out of the implementation, and I didn't want to tie us to
supporting that behavior.  I also wanted the survey conventions to
be as consistent and simple as possible.

E.g. -nB is documented, but -n^SLfoo is not.  What you've pointed
out is a case I forgot to consider, but which is related.

First, here's what # Babyl B's documentation says:

    Survey all or a range of messages.
    Survey argument convention:
	No argument means survey all messages in the Babyl file.
->	One positive argument n means survey the next n messages.
->	One negative argument -n means survey the previous n messages.
	Two arguments  m,n  mean survey n messages
	    starting with message number m.

while here's what Survey Labeled Messages's documentation says:

    Survey all or some messages with some label.
    String argument is label.  Messages with that label will be surveyed.
    Survey argument convention:
	No argument means survey all labeled messages in the Babyl file.
->	One positive argument n means survey the next n labeled messages.
	Two arguments  m,n  mean survey n labeled messages
	    starting with message number m.

Note the missing line.

Unfortunately the m,n case does not mention whether n can be
negative, leaving open the question of what it means to "survey
-3 labeled messages".  You probably read that as "survey 3 of
them, going backwards".  I think we should simply change the
documentation to read:

	Two arguments  m,n  mean survey n labeled messages
	    starting with message number m.  N must be positive.

