This is a bug in the Babyl standalone mode. The problem is that there are
many nested errsets and though one errset caught one error, the unwinding
process probably caused another URK which was not caught until an outer
errset which was not really intended to catch such things. The result was
that Babyl exited normally and when Babyl runs in standalone mode, normal
exit is supposed to kill it. If this behavior bothers you (it can't lose
mail; it can only lose a few D's or an unfinished M or such as that), then
call Babyl from inside Emacs instead of standalone. Trapping URKs is *very*
hard; trapping PURs is even harder... I guess you know you're lucky things 
run at all when you're out of address space. I'm sure there are any number 
of programs that don't do even that well...

