	    <RICH.11997971102.BABYL@MIT-OZ>

    Date: 9 Mar 1984  10:18 EST (Fri)
    From: Charles Rich <RICH%MIT-OZ at MIT-MC.ARPA>

        Date: Friday, 9 March 1984  10:13-EST
        From: JMILLER at MIT-OZ <JMiller%MIT-OZ at MIT-MC>
        Sender: JMILLER
        To:   *PS:<RICH>MAIL.TXT.1@MIT-OZ
        cc:   bug-babyl at MC
        Re:   Parsing Error in To-Field

        My mail system (HERMES) looks in the mail forwarding data base to
        find your correct address.  It then substitutes *PS:....  in and
        that fouls up babyl...

    Yes, I agree that what HERMES does is consistent...

No. If I understand correctly from your descriptions, what HERMES does 
is not correct.

The address

   *PS:<RICH>MAIL.TXT.1@MIT-OZ 

is not in valid RFC822 format. It is fine for such an address to be in
the mail database on OZ because that database can define whatever format
it wants, but it is not fine for HERMES to pick up things in that format
and put them in a mail header. The reason is that "<" and ">" are 
reserved markers such that in

    Joe Luser <LUSER @ MIT-OZ>

only the LUSER@MIT-OZ part will be seen as an address. To quote the
<...> so it is not interpreted in this way, 

    "*PS:<RICH>MAIL.TXT.1"@MIT-OZ

must be generated by HERMES when it resolves the addresses. 

Personally, I think it is completely bogus for HERMES to be putting
the resolved addresses in the header. Fine for it to want to resolve
this info for the purposes of sending the mail, but not fine for it
to put that resolved info in the header. If, for example, you were
sending to INFO-FOO and that resolved to RICH which resolved to 
*PS:<RICH>... and you put the *PS:<RICH>... in the message header,
then people are going to later reply to there, preempting Chuck's
ability to either remove himself from INFO-FOO or to change where
mail to RICH goes.

