    Re:   More ' problems

    In ' mode, C-W deletes some part of your survey buffer, rather than
    giving the line count for the message I've got displayed in the 
    other window.

That's not a bug, that's a feature!

You are allowed to edit your survey buffer. You can rearrange the lines,
you can c-K lines you didn't mean to survey or are done surveying, etc.

The general rule is that control chars do their editing function and
self inserting characters do their Babyl function. If you want a command
like c-W to work in Survey mode as a Babyl command, use c-Q c-W. There
is one exception: c-D behaves as a self-inserting character (ie, runs its
Babyl function). This is handled by an explicit special case in the code.

You might make a case that Return should be treated as a self-inserting
character even though it is not (it has hacks to optimize use of existing 
blank lines after the cursor to minimize redisplay) and perhaps it is also
deserving of a special case. I dunno. Personally, I always flush arguments
with c-G.

In ZBabyl, you may find other commands like c-Q c-X useful for getting 
the ZBabyl c-X comtab to do things like set start and expiration dates, etc.
Beware, though: since you are running inside a c-Q, c-G is turned off and
quitting out of commands that prompt can only be done by over-rubout.

I won't claim this is an ideal interface, but it basically works and is
predictable if you know the rules. Good luck.
-kmp

