Date: 4 April 1984 17:35-EST
From: Kent M Pitman <KMP @ MIT-MC>
Subject: Problems with & Autolabel Subject Labels
To: BUG-BABYL @ MIT-MC
cc: ALAN @ MIT-MC, KMP @ MIT-MC

ALAN's Babyl file was being trashed in a repeatable fashion. He and I just
spent the last couple of hours tracking down the problem.

& Autolabel Subject Labels does not restrict itself to labeling messages
which are recent. This is a bug in itself since presumably its function
is just to suggest labels and you should be able to modify  that suggestion
later (eg, by removing those labels) without it forcing the labels back.

In any case, this has the bad problem that if it adds or deletes labels
which are not in the "recent" area, then the 0f[vb and 0f[vz done at the
beginning of that macro are violated because the distance from the real
buffer edge to the edge of the recent area has been modified and when the
implicit f]vz and f]vb are done later by the ^\, the buffer bounds get
set back to the wrong thing. Typically, you overrun just slightly into a
message you didn't mean to, and so that little piece of message gets moved
by the ^P  -.  ...  if Append:2 is enabled to a different part of the
buffer making it seem as if the mail was yanked into the wrong place in
the buffer (which is not the case). I suppose if Append:2 is not selected,
this bug may not show itself at all, which may be one reason that this has
not been linked to & Autolabel Subject Labels in the past.

I wouldn't be at all surprised if this accounted for other until-now
mysterious lossages with Babyl. It's worth asking others with trashed Babyl
files whether they use subject labelling, what their append option is, and
if they have recently edited (removed) any labels automatically supplied by
the auto-labeler.

I suggest the right thing is to make & Autolabel Subject Labels work only
across the region of new mail. Failing that, the next best ideas would be 
either to make & Autolabel remember its position by message number or
to have it notice when it is doing labelling and use an FN construct to 
restore the buffer bounds later by a more sophisticated means than 
simple f[vb, etc.

Feel free to send mail to me or ALAN if this isn't a clear enough description
of the problem. -kmp

