Subject: a few questions
In-reply-to: Msg of 11 Apr 1984  13:37-EST from STRAZ%MIT-OZ at MIT-MC.ARPA

As Babyl is part of EMACS, ^T is a character command and not the
standard Tops-20 information command.  Babyl should at least
display the load average for you when you type ^T, and I'll keep
the feature request in mind.  (It is trivial.)

You can only read Tops-20 format mail files.  You need a Babyl
file to be able to edit; you need one Babyl file for each mail
file.  Easy to create:  For example, for mail file FOO.MAIL.1,
to create FOO.BABYL, type (to Babyl):

    X Create Babyl FileFOO.BABYL<return>
    and answer its various questions.  In particular, when it
    asks what the mail file name is type FOO.MAIL.1.

Then, you I to FOO.BABYL when you want to read the mail.  One
unfortunate aspec of all this -- it will not let you read with MM
sometimes, Babyl other times, since MM wants Tops-20 mail files.

There is no very good way to reorder messages within Babyl.  It
is possible, in at least a few different ways, though.  One way
is to O these messages to a temporary file, say TEMP.XMAIL, in
the order you want, deleting the messages from the regular Babyl
file as you do this.  Then, I to TEMP.XMAIL, and O them back to
the regular Babyl file.  Ugh, but possible.

To get your full personal name to appear, set the Babyl option
variable  Babyl Personal Name, e.g. in your EMACS.VARS file, you
might have the line:

Babyl Personal Name: "Steve Strassmann"

