Subject: RFC 934

A careful reading of the subject RFC (a proposal for message
encapsulation) may reveal a possible conflict with the way Undigestify
now expects digests to be formatted.  In particular, the authors of
the RFC claim:

1.  "At present there is no unambiguous standard for interest group
digests...  Although interest group digests may appear to conform to a
pseudo-standard, there is a serious ambiguity in the implementations
which produce digests."

2.  "Currently (in existing digestification agents), an encapsulation
boundary (EB) is defined as a line in the message which starts with a
dash (decimal code 45, "-").  Initially, no restriction is placed on
the length of the encapsulation boundary, or on the characters that
follow the dash."

There's much more: forwarded and remailed messages are considered
special cases of message encapsulation, as are Bcc:'d messages.  These
deserve consideration as does the proposed scheme for "forwarding"
encapsulated messages, leading to the possible extension of
UnDigestify to handle these cases.

--Frank

