    that want the old behavior, just put in a customizing variable.

This would be a sort of kneejerk fix to a more complicated problem.
The problem is not really at the level of CC or To, but of the list
itself. If the sender of the original message had To'd instead of Cc'd
the long lists, extra mail would be generated. Many people don't make
the distinction between To and Cc that your message seems to presuppose.
Also, there might be individuals CC'd who want to get the reply which the
user thinks he shouldn't include. 

In spite of mailer overhead caused by this sort of thing, it's not really
that hard to type "D" to most mail readers to make spurious mail go away,
and it is very hard to find information that got misrouted due to dropped
recipients.

The right solution is to inform users of the importance of correctly
selecting a set of recipients, giving them an understanding of the 
overhead in sending to large lists, and an appreciation for when they
should and shouldn't include such things. I'll grant you that such
instruction is frequently neglected, but it's no reason to penalize
people who know what's going on. Generating spurious mail is, after all,
not generally destructive -- just tedious.

The question of defaults is really completely orthogonal to this. In the
end, it's easier to c-W an unwanted region in Emacs than it is to type
in the stuff that didn't get included (a similar argument to the one I used
above about the "D" key, by the way -- note the pattern). 

Well-meaning various people have, from time to time, made this suggestion 
and it's never been changed, I suspect for reasons like those I've outlined
here.

    Also, some modifier of C-M-Y might allow you to yank in the CC's
    if you decide you want them later.

This part is novel, but would probably be slightly hairy to implement
and probably equally hard to explain to people (I have found many people
to be confused by the use of numeric args as modifiers to commands).
Also, you have to remember to call it. The current behavior has the
advantage of making something visible in the header to remind you that
there were CC'd people.

Of course, we're all crossing our fingers that better mailer technologies 
come along to make these issues moot. Eg, such systems might allow large
mailing lists to more conveniently get screened, or to allow mailers to
at least query the mail system about whether an address refers to an
individual or group, so that it can conditionally advise the user when 
it thinks he may be sending to an excessive number of people... We've
discussed (not necessarily seriously) changing the Dont-Reply-To list 
to something more like Dont-Send-To so that no matter how such mail is
generated (via the "R" command or the "M" command), the user still gets 
queried if he tries to send to certain classes of lists. 

