     Babyl and MM are both obsolete programs, written for dead computers
and operating systems.  Let's not forget the equally doomed status of
24x80 fixed-font ASCII terminals and a model of electronic mail where
each user has a byte stream of characters in a "mail file" on his
directory.

     So -- of course something better than MM and Babyl will come along.
I sincerely doubt that it will be especially developed for PDP-10's or
for TOPS-20 (a dead OS) or ITS (an even more moribund OS).  I would also
think that a lot more than MM and Babyl will be looked at in its
development.  While MM is the undoubted #1 TOPS-20 mail system, Hermes,
MAIL/RDMAIL (DEC's bundled TOPS-20 mail software), and DECmail/MS (a DEC
MM clone taken from MM circa 1979) are all in much wider use than Babyl.
While we can ignore the DEC stuff, we can't ignore Hermes.  If MM is the
BMW of mail software then Hermes is the Cadillac (at 4MPG!).  But that
isn't the point -- there is a lot more out there than just the small world
of PDP-10 mail software, much of which has substantially different models
than anything ever done on TOPS-20.

     One of my notions has been a distributed mail database much like
Sweden's COM.  In COM, only one copy of the message exists, in a centralized
mail service base.  The recipients of the message are sent pointers to that
message.  Presumably the message is archived once all the pointers are
deleted.  The next logical step is, of course, access over the network to
the mail database.

     Still another notion has to do with some of the improvements in user
interface possible with more advanced user/machine hardware -- bitmapped
displays, mice, ad nauseum.  The tricky part is to figure out how to get
all the needs integrated together in such a manner that the system as a
whole is usable and does what is needed.  The MIT style of Lisp machines
are a good example of a valiant attempt in that direction; they are also
a good example of what happens to good intentions.  Not that Lisp machines
are bad or anything; rather that the problems they solve and fail to solve
are an excellent learning experience for anybody who feels that human
engineering is trivial.

     Speaking solely as an MM developer, MM was a wonderful program when
it was first written...8 years ago.  The fact that it took over in the
TOPS-20 world is a tribute to how good it was/is.  However, I recognize
the need to move on, and for a while now I have been trying to obtain
funding to develop something now.  Unfortunately, them that funda are more
interested in funding more work on MM (which has been proven to be useful)
than on funding all new R&D.  Needless to say I am still trying (with a
reasonable amount of hope) and so are many others.

-- Mark --
