     There's a difference between what operating systems will
dominate and what operating systems are alive.  There are far
more CP/M, MS-DOS, and VM/370 (and successor) systems in the
world than Unix systems.  My personal belief is that all of these
unit-record TTY 33 oriented operating systems (which include
Unix) are dinosaurs.

     Unix's sole redeeming feature is that it is portable.  In
this day and age of throw-away hardware portable software is
crucial.  However, Unix remains a minicomputer operating system
with a toy filesystem and an arcane user interface.

     Hermes runs on Tenex and TOPS-20, and was developed by BBN.
It is closer to MM in interface than Babyl, and is more powerful.
It is also larger and *much* slower than MM.  However, it's
really big with the military folks.  They'd probably use Hermes
exclusively if it weren't for the fact that it is so slow on many
systems you have to use MM just to get work done.  Because of
that, about 2/3 of that world has moved to MM.  A number of
devout Hermes users still exist, mostly because there are things
that Hermes can do that no other mail software can do.

     Privacy in electronic mail is a complete and total joke.
The privacy of electronic mail is only as much as the computer
facility it runs on chooses to grant.  Anybody who believes that
any electronic mail is private is engaging in dangerous self-
delusion.  Anybody who believes that ARPA mail -- and especially
MIT mail -- is private is totally off the wall.

     COM is set up by the universities in Sweden and, I think,
