From: Benjamin Kuipers <BEN@MIT-MC>
Subject:  suggested feature
To: BUG-BABYL@MIT-MC
Message-ID: <[MIT-MC].512576.850521.BEN>

(I'm sure you're tired of suggested features, but this is a good one.)

I find myself keeping a number of messages in my babyl file, not because
I am interested in the contents anymore, but because it is the easiest way
to retrieve complex return addresses for people.  I use the B listing to
list all my saved messages, Jump to the right one, and Reply (for the
n-th time) just to get the To: field set correctly.  Clearly sub-optimal.

Given the problem, the design of the solution is clear; perhaps even
more so to you than me.  I want the facility for a small,
neatly-organized database, preferably with both human-name and
net-address, that I can scan, point to an address, and say, "Mail to
that person".  Sequential visual search of an alphabetically organized
file is fine, say driven by incremental string-search.  If someone has
a larger set of friends than that, they need a different program.

Unfortunately, this simple idea immediately expands into zillions of other
closely-related features that doubtless complexify the design:  adding people
to cc: fields, defining mailing lists, insertion of addresses, etc.

Nonetheless, this is clearly a real problem that will only get worse as the
network world gets more complex.  Also clearly, babyl is the right tool to
solve it with.

Thanks for listening.

				Ben

