Subject: dropping to lower case
In-reply-to: Msg of 6 Aug 1986  15:15-EDT from David Kirsh <KIRSH>

    Date: Wednesday, 6 August 1986  15:15-EDT
    From: David Kirsh <KIRSH>
    To:   bug-babyl
    Re:   dropping to lower case

    I've got s few bugs with my babyl.  

    1) If I pick up my babyl fork from top level by using continue, then
    if I ^L to refresh the screen it converts a region to lower case.

You're probably exiting with ^X^C.  EMACS sees the ^X, but never sees
the ^C (the EXEC gets it first and halts the fork).  Then, when you
continue and type ^L, EMACS sees ^X^L which is ^R Lowercase Region...

Cure:  exit with ^X^Z.  This is a much more graceful exit, in that it
lets EMACS do whatever autosaving etc it wants to do first.

    2) When I delete a portion of a message before ^o outputting to a file
    I often get an URK Q-register or PDL underfill or overflow.  I don't know
    what my kill ring has to do with this loop, but I often get that
    message.  I'll try to keep track of other incidents.

This is almost certainly due to the fact that your Babyl file is 142
pages long.  EMACS, with all its various libraries, including Babyl
(which is quite large), plus a large Babyl file, is dangerously close
to simply running out of address space---you only get 2^18 words,
period.  When you kill a portion of a message using ^W or whatever, it
gets added to your kill ring, further increasing your total required
space...  etc.

Usually, you get an URK.  I've noticed instances, usually with very
big Babyl files and/or lots of loaded libraries, where EMACS will get
illegal memory writes and/or reads, as if there's something broken
with its memory allocation strategy.  Various PDL problems may be
related to this.

Cure:  halve the size of your Babyl file.

    If you can do anything I'll be delighted.

    			-- David

