    Date: Monday, 1 June 1987  15:12-EDT
    From: RIG@XX.LCS.MIT.EDU

    It seems that when you have a lot of messages in your babyl file and
    you start going through them issuing lots of commands, you are prone
    to getting a message which says something like "pushdown stack full".
    Then you seem to be in the painful situation of not even being able to
    issue a q command in order to save the file with all the deletions you
    have made and to start over.  The only quasi-solution people around
    here seem to know of is to issue a ^c and reset the thing, so that you
    lose all the changes you've made while in babyl.  Could someone please
    improve the operation of the program so it will say something before
    reaching this dreadfully wedged state, so that you can save your
    changes.  I'm also surprised that when you do an e and and s command,
    you don't seem to get any resetting of state which would delay the
    occurence of this pushdown stack full business.

Well, if the pushdown stack overflows it's not surprising that you
can't call any more routines (after all, what would they use for a
stack?).  Unless you are doing something like using C-X M inside
itself a lot, this is probably just some routine that forgets to
execute a ^\ after pushing a lot of junk on the stack.

You can get out of this if you're willing to talk to TECO directly.
If you can, get into a minibuffer and execute a ^W to get back to
TECO's main command loop.  If you can't get into a minibuffer
(likely), just start typing lots of harmless characters (like <Space>)
until you overload the error handler and it throws you into TECO.
From TECO you can get back to BABYL by doing
	:M(M.M BABYL$)$$
If that doesn't work, try doing
	M(M.M Select Buffer$)*Babyl*$$
	M(M.M Write File$)BABYL.EXPLODED$$
	^Z
which will at least dump out the current in-memory state of your BABYL
file to a disk file of your choosing (you probably don't want to
overwrite your old BABYL file until you know what state the new one is
in).

A more useful thing to do would be to find out which routine is
neglecting to fix the stack.  I can't give you a script for doing
that, you'd have to know TECO and the EMACS debugger to start with.

--Rob

